01:20.620 --> 01:22.720
Hello, welcome to another
episode of "Comic Book Men,"

01:22.722 --> 01:24.722
the only show that's
so happy to see you,

01:24.724 --> 01:26.557
we show you our Batpole.

01:26.559 --> 01:28.226
- I'm Kevin Smith.
- Bryan Johnson.

01:28.228 --> 01:29.594
- Walt Flanagan.
- Mike Zapcic.

01:29.596 --> 01:31.062
- Ming Chen.
- Awesome.

01:31.064 --> 01:33.631
What flew into the shop
this week, gentlemen?

01:33.633 --> 01:35.700
It's a rarity, but
every once in a while,

01:35.702 --> 01:38.903
something will pique my
interest beyond ridiculing it.

01:38.905 --> 01:41.906
<i>[funky music]</i>

01:41.908 --> 01:48.045
<i>♪
♪</i>

01:48.047 --> 01:49.647
- Hey, how you doing?
- Lou, how are you today?

01:49.649 --> 01:52.617
- Good. Oh.
- Got a toy from 1973.

01:52.619 --> 01:54.986
Check it out, Bry. Evel
Knievel Stunt Cycle.

01:54.988 --> 01:58.456
- Oh, hello.
- [All laugh].

01:58.458 --> 02:00.658
I've experienced my first nerdgasm.

02:00.660 --> 02:02.059
[all laugh]

02:02.061 --> 02:05.963
This was probably my
favorite toy growing up.

02:05.965 --> 02:08.966
<i>[hard rock music]</i>

02:08.967 --> 02:13.571
<i>♪
♪</i>

02:13.573 --> 02:15.339
Is this your original stunt cycle?

02:15.341 --> 02:16.841
Actually, no.

02:16.843 --> 02:18.309
I was sitting around work
one day talking to the guys

02:18.311 --> 02:20.177
and reminiscing about our favorite toys

02:20.179 --> 02:22.313
when we were growing up and the
first thing that came to my mind

02:22.315 --> 02:23.814
was Evel Knievel toys, and...

02:23.816 --> 02:25.149
Yellow! [all laugh]

02:25.151 --> 02:26.584
I started collecting 'em,

02:26.586 --> 02:27.652
and, uh, ended up with duplicates, so...

02:27.654 --> 02:29.086
Oh, okay.

02:29.088 --> 02:30.421
Brought this one in to get rid of it.

02:30.423 --> 02:32.490
Wow. On a personal level,

02:32.492 --> 02:34.859
I wanted to be Evel Knievel.

02:34.861 --> 02:37.428
- He was a national phenomenon.
- Oh, yeah.

02:37.430 --> 02:39.163
How many children's bones

02:39.165 --> 02:41.966
is Evel Knievel
responsible for breaking?

02:41.968 --> 02:43.267
- Gotta be millions.
- Right?

02:43.269 --> 02:44.502
Gotta be millions at this point.

02:44.504 --> 02:46.037
Could you carry on being a daredevil

02:46.039 --> 02:48.506
if you knew kids were
emulating you and getting hurt?

02:48.508 --> 02:50.107
You know why he could?

02:50.109 --> 02:51.842
He was always telling
his fans to wear helmets.

02:51.844 --> 02:53.177
- [chuckles]
- You still can get

02:53.179 --> 02:55.279
horrifically injured
even wearing a helmet.

02:55.281 --> 02:56.947
Yeah, as he proved, like,

02:56.949 --> 02:59.016
multiple times, like, doing jumps.

02:59.018 --> 03:00.618
[all laugh]

03:00.620 --> 03:02.186
What do you think he's most known for?

03:02.188 --> 03:04.488
- Snake Canyon.
- [laughs]

03:04.490 --> 03:05.956
- Right?
- Snake River Canyon.

03:05.958 --> 03:08.492
Oh, my God, how big an event was that?

03:08.494 --> 03:11.228
- It was like the Olympics.
- Yeah, like, what nut

03:11.230 --> 03:13.164
puts himself into a rocket,

03:13.166 --> 03:15.966
says he's gonna jump
a canyon successfully?

03:15.968 --> 03:18.736
- Oh, Evel.
- [All laugh]

03:18.738 --> 03:20.971
Only in America can you
get famous by being like,

03:20.973 --> 03:22.406
"Hey, watch me jump something!"

03:22.408 --> 03:24.008
Like, "I don't care."
Like, "I might die!"

03:24.010 --> 03:25.376
They're like, "Oh,
ooh, yeah." [all laugh]

03:25.378 --> 03:27.678
Was it the most
talked-about stunt ever? Yes.

03:27.680 --> 03:29.680
Did he make it across all the way?

03:29.682 --> 03:31.082
No. But still...

03:31.084 --> 03:32.717
Did he float to the ground in defeat?

03:32.719 --> 03:34.985
[all laugh] Yes.

03:34.987 --> 03:36.921
- Do you remember how it works?
- I do believe,

03:36.923 --> 03:39.757
if I'm not mistaken... okay,
got your little rivets here

03:39.759 --> 03:41.859
that they pop in.

03:41.861 --> 03:45.196
So you haven't performed this procedure

03:45.198 --> 03:47.598
in almost 40 years, I imagine.

03:47.600 --> 03:48.866
Yeah, close to it.

03:48.868 --> 03:50.000
Think you still got it in you

03:50.002 --> 03:51.502
to make it do a trick or anything?

03:51.504 --> 03:52.903
I think I'm still a young enough buck

03:52.905 --> 03:54.772
that I can at least get one revolution.

03:54.774 --> 03:56.707
[all laugh]

03:56.709 --> 03:58.209
Look at him go. [toy whirring]

03:58.211 --> 04:00.211
Just listen to that
sound, just that revving.

04:00.213 --> 04:03.013
[toy whirring] Here he goes!

04:03.015 --> 04:04.682
- Oh!
- Oh.

04:04.684 --> 04:07.118
- Just like real life.
- Yeah.

04:07.120 --> 04:08.719
Broke his femur.

04:08.721 --> 04:10.187
- Poor Evel.
- Look at you, man.

04:10.189 --> 04:11.689
Lookit, you got a grin on your face.

04:11.691 --> 04:12.923
- Yeah.
- You know?

04:12.925 --> 04:14.392
Really, you got a sparkle in your eye.

04:14.394 --> 04:16.226
- Happier times
- A little hop in your step.

04:16.228 --> 04:17.962
That's all it took was that, huh?

04:17.964 --> 04:20.630
- That's all it took.
- [All chuckle]

04:20.632 --> 04:22.400
So, you coming in here to sell it today?

04:22.402 --> 04:23.801
I'm coming in to sell it.

04:23.803 --> 04:25.403
I'm looking to get about $150 for it.

04:25.405 --> 04:27.104
One of us is definitely
interested, right?

04:27.106 --> 04:28.439
You wouldn't want it for the store?

04:28.441 --> 04:30.741
I... you know, how
could I do that to you?

04:30.743 --> 04:32.710
This has gotta be for you, man.

04:32.712 --> 04:35.479
$150? That is a lot, though.

04:35.481 --> 04:36.947
How can you put a price on that...

04:36.949 --> 04:38.249
On that happiness you just felt?

04:38.251 --> 04:39.650
I know, it's priceless.

04:39.652 --> 04:41.752
I mean, really, I'm
not gonna display it.

04:41.754 --> 04:43.053
I don't care about the box.

04:43.055 --> 04:45.556
I would actually let
my niece play with it.

04:45.558 --> 04:47.391
Would you go $95?

04:47.393 --> 04:50.394
$95.

04:50.396 --> 04:51.462
Make it $100 and we got a deal.

04:51.464 --> 04:53.063
Oh.

04:53.065 --> 04:54.999
All right. We'll be friends.

04:55.001 --> 04:56.834
<i>- [funky music]
- Ahhhh.</i>

04:56.836 --> 04:58.169
- There you go.
- Sounds good.

04:58.171 --> 04:59.637
<i>♪
♪</i>

04:59.639 --> 05:01.338
Eh?

05:01.340 --> 05:02.640
All right, Ming.

05:02.642 --> 05:04.341
I won't let him fall off the edge.

05:04.343 --> 05:06.110
- Here we go.
- Uh-oh, uh-oh.

05:06.112 --> 05:08.145
[toy whirs and clicks]

05:08.147 --> 05:09.847
- Oh, my God.
- [laughs]

05:09.849 --> 05:11.482
- No, no, no.
- I need to get my money back!

05:11.484 --> 05:13.684
- [all laughing]
- Get him, Ming, get him!

05:15.420 --> 05:17.288
John! Hey, what are you doing here?

05:17.290 --> 05:19.156
You guys said to stop
by, so I'm stoppin' by.

05:19.158 --> 05:20.791
This is John Romita, Jr.,

05:20.793 --> 05:22.760
Comic book art royalty.

05:22.762 --> 05:25.262
I called in about the
Treasury Edition Wonder Woman?

05:25.264 --> 05:27.264
There it is: Wonder
Woman kicking Nazi ass.

05:39.047 --> 05:40.610
- Ming.
- Hey, John, what's going on?

05:40.627 --> 05:42.426
- How's it going?
- What are you doing here?

05:42.428 --> 05:43.694
- John.
- Hey.

05:43.696 --> 05:45.363
Good to see you.

05:45.365 --> 05:46.631
Yeah, you guys said to
stop by, so I'm stoppin' by.

05:46.633 --> 05:48.132
Pleasure to meet you. Big fan.

05:48.134 --> 05:49.867
Thank you very much.
This place is beautiful.

05:49.869 --> 05:52.537
Can I bring this to a
screeching halt and say,

05:52.539 --> 05:54.205
"You're an artist?"

05:54.207 --> 05:55.706
[all laugh]

05:55.708 --> 05:57.608
This is a legend right here.

05:57.610 --> 05:58.877
I just hang out here,
I don't work here...

05:59.014 --> 06:00.378
- That's all right.
- So I'm not too familiar.

06:00.380 --> 06:01.445
This is John Romita, Jr.,

06:01.447 --> 06:03.748
son of John Romita, Sr.

06:03.750 --> 06:05.149
I'm not really a "junior," actually.

06:05.151 --> 06:06.417
- No?
- It's a pen name.

06:06.419 --> 06:07.885
We have different middle names.

06:07.887 --> 06:09.887
This must be blowing
your mind right now.

06:09.889 --> 06:12.323
We're talking comic
book art royalty, here.

06:12.325 --> 06:13.724
- That's nice, thank you.
- I mean,

06:13.726 --> 06:15.660
we're lucky the carpet is red.

06:15.662 --> 06:16.761
[all laugh]

06:16.763 --> 06:18.596
Wow.

06:18.598 --> 06:21.999
J-R-J-R. Son
of J-R-S-R,

06:22.001 --> 06:24.936
seminal Spider-Man
artist John Romita, Sr.

06:24.938 --> 06:26.804
He has worked on some of the most

06:26.806 --> 06:29.273
iconic superhero titles to work on.

06:29.275 --> 06:30.942
He followed his father on Spider-Man

06:30.944 --> 06:33.411
<i>and did his own legendary
run on Spider-Man.</i>

06:33.413 --> 06:35.613
He's on a long run on Daredevil.

06:35.615 --> 06:37.148
<i>Daredevil as well.</i>

06:37.150 --> 06:39.250
And he's working on Superman right now.

06:39.252 --> 06:40.985
<i>He's one of the world's
greatest comic book artists.</i>

06:40.987 --> 06:42.820
Just happened to be that his dad

06:42.822 --> 06:44.322
is also one of the world's
greatest comic book artists.

06:44.324 --> 06:45.823
[all chuckling]

06:45.825 --> 06:47.592
He's a legend, but he's always been cool

06:47.594 --> 06:49.193
with me and Mike when we go to cons,

06:49.195 --> 06:50.461
so I've always invited
him down to the store.

06:50.463 --> 06:51.762
He's from Long Island.

06:51.764 --> 06:54.098
"Any time you're nearby, come on down."

06:54.100 --> 06:55.499
And he came down.

06:55.501 --> 06:57.868
So what was it like to
grow up in that house?

06:57.870 --> 06:59.203
It was such a novelty.

06:59.205 --> 07:00.705
People would come up to me and say,

07:00.707 --> 07:02.206
"Do you know your
father does Spider-Man?"

07:02.208 --> 07:03.774
- [laughter]
- Yeah.

07:03.776 --> 07:05.376
"Do you know who that was,
just came to your house?

07:05.378 --> 07:06.444
Sta... That was Jack Kirby.
No, that was Stan Lee."

07:06.446 --> 07:07.845
You know, that kind of thing.

07:07.847 --> 07:09.113
Other kids, when they asked me about it,

07:09.115 --> 07:10.681
I didn't think of it that way.

07:10.683 --> 07:12.116
It was just life... that's
just the way it is, right?

07:12.118 --> 07:13.451
- Yeah, it was fun.
- Can you imagine

07:13.453 --> 07:14.852
those other people you hang out with,

07:14.854 --> 07:16.287
like, after school...
It was like Uncle Stan.

07:16.289 --> 07:18.823
And then my dad out there, John Romita.

07:18.825 --> 07:20.458
Obviously it had a
great influence on you.

07:20.460 --> 07:22.360
It did, just by watching them, though,

07:22.362 --> 07:23.995
seeing them work together.

07:23.997 --> 07:25.997
Stan would act out
the plot in the office,

07:25.999 --> 07:27.898
jumpin' off the sides of the chairs,

07:27.900 --> 07:29.567
and my father'd be sitting
there writing notes,

07:29.569 --> 07:31.302
and I would come into the
office in the summertime,

07:31.304 --> 07:33.304
when school was out, and
watch the two of them.

07:33.306 --> 07:34.905
It was pretty amazing.

07:34.907 --> 07:36.607
What a different process
from now, where it's like,

07:36.609 --> 07:37.842
you get an email.

07:37.844 --> 07:39.977
[all laugh]

07:39.979 --> 07:41.712
The living legends at that time,

07:41.714 --> 07:44.548
walking in and out of his house,
talking comics, drawing comics,

07:44.550 --> 07:46.183
right in front of him as a kid.

07:46.185 --> 07:48.052
Wow, man. People who've contributed work

07:48.054 --> 07:50.988
that still resonates and echoes
through the halls of eternity.

07:50.990 --> 07:54.425
Names that even I recognize,
like industry giants.

07:54.427 --> 07:57.028
When I was young, I remember
having my dad's friend

07:57.030 --> 08:00.231
Uncle Butch come over and pour
a can of Schlitz beer on my head.

08:00.233 --> 08:01.999
[all laugh]

08:02.001 --> 08:03.668
We didn't have stories like that.

08:03.670 --> 08:05.770
Were you into Spider-Man and comics...

08:05.772 --> 08:07.538
- No.
- Or were you introduced to

08:07.540 --> 08:09.774
- comics through his work?
- Just through his work.

08:09.776 --> 08:11.342
He was doing romance books for D.C.

08:11.344 --> 08:14.278
And I would sit below his
table, and I would watch,

08:14.280 --> 08:16.113
and be bored to tears and leave.

08:16.115 --> 08:17.715
[all laugh]

08:17.717 --> 08:19.283
- Secret shame.
- And that was it.

08:19.285 --> 08:21.919
And one day, he was working
on "Daredevil" ♪12,

08:21.921 --> 08:23.387
I remember it vividly.

08:23.389 --> 08:24.722
Daredevil surrounded
by all the bad guys,

08:24.724 --> 08:26.123
so how's he going to get out of it?

08:26.125 --> 08:27.425
And he explained, "He's a superhero,

08:27.427 --> 08:29.560
and he also happens to be blind."

08:29.562 --> 08:31.629
And I think the top of my head exploded.

08:31.631 --> 08:34.765
And that moment was just
a turning point to me,

08:34.767 --> 08:37.134
because I... he told
me I stayed by his side

08:37.135 --> 08:39.203
for days at a time
after that, just drawing.

08:39.205 --> 08:40.404
I was seven or eight years old.

08:40.405 --> 08:42.306
Because of that issue of "Daredevil?"

08:42.308 --> 08:44.107
That moment. I had to find
out what this was all about,

08:44.110 --> 08:45.643
'cause of my father.

08:45.645 --> 08:49.080
- It has to be genetic, right?
- I don't know.

08:49.082 --> 08:52.283
Before my father, my
grandfather was a woodworker.

08:52.285 --> 08:53.984
Worked on coffins.

08:53.986 --> 08:56.821
My brother is brilliant, but
never artistic the way I was,

08:56.823 --> 08:59.990
and for some reason, it filtered
down to me, I don't know.

08:59.992 --> 09:01.992
Listen, my artwork is okay.

09:01.994 --> 09:03.928
I followed him, I've
been influenced by him,

09:03.930 --> 09:05.730
but I'm not anywhere in his class.

09:05.732 --> 09:08.232
He's Michael Jordan, I'm
the sixth guy on the bench.

09:08.234 --> 09:10.401
He's still Michael Jordan,
but you're Scottie Pippen.

09:10.403 --> 09:11.936
Oh, thank you! [laughter]

09:11.938 --> 09:14.105
You still have the ring!
You still got the rings.

09:14.107 --> 09:15.639
- Still got the rings, my friend.
- All right!

09:15.641 --> 09:17.308
That's a nice analogy.
I appreciate that.

09:17.310 --> 09:19.477
In his mind, he'll always be the guy

09:19.479 --> 09:20.578
that became an artist.

09:20.580 --> 09:22.613
His dad was the artist,

09:22.615 --> 09:24.281
from the moment he knew him, so,

09:24.283 --> 09:26.751
I got to imagine the
guy defers to his dad.

09:26.753 --> 09:28.452
I would look at that guy like a hero.

09:28.454 --> 09:30.087
My dad worked at the post office,

09:30.089 --> 09:31.422
and I thought it was great.

09:31.424 --> 09:33.791
[all laugh]

09:33.793 --> 09:35.993
Guys like Jack Kirby and my father

09:35.995 --> 09:37.361
caused the industry to grow.

09:37.363 --> 09:38.796
We, as contemporaries...

09:38.798 --> 09:40.698
The Jim Lees, you know, the Kuberts...

09:40.700 --> 09:43.634
We watched the industry
grow while we were in it,

09:43.636 --> 09:45.369
Speaking of Jim Lee, this is...

09:45.371 --> 09:47.271
I'm looking at something
beautiful on the wall.

09:47.273 --> 09:48.706
Yeah, one of our prized pieces.

09:48.708 --> 09:50.174
That used to be a fire
door, and uh, we thought...

09:50.176 --> 09:51.942
We thought it'd be the perfect easel.

09:51.944 --> 09:53.644
- Is that why it's red?
- That's why it's red.

09:53.646 --> 09:54.879
- Brilliant.
- He came in,

09:54.881 --> 09:56.580
and did that in one night.

09:56.582 --> 09:58.015
That's amazing. I don't
know, I think you need...

09:58.017 --> 10:00.718
Jim Lee, Romita Jr. piece, you know.

10:00.720 --> 10:01.819
- Whoa!
- Are you offering?

10:01.821 --> 10:03.587
- [laughter]
- Uh, no.

10:03.589 --> 10:05.389
- You know, you're here.
- We'd find some wall space

10:05.391 --> 10:07.324
for a John Romita, Jr. piece.

10:07.326 --> 10:08.692
You want me to turn
that lead on right now?

10:08.694 --> 10:10.528
[all laugh]

10:10.530 --> 10:12.496
That would be an honor,
especially if I can

10:12.498 --> 10:14.031
get in the same proximity as Jim's work.

10:14.033 --> 10:15.566
- That's...
- Oh, yeah.

10:15.568 --> 10:17.034
I'm a big fan of his,
so I would love to.

10:17.036 --> 10:18.169
- [exhales]
- Sure, that would be awesome.

10:18.171 --> 10:19.570
Let me run down to the basement.

10:19.572 --> 10:21.071
I got some pencils. I
got a big sheet of paper.

10:21.073 --> 10:22.740
- You got it.
- All right, thanks, man.

10:22.742 --> 10:24.008
My pleasure.

10:24.010 --> 10:25.309
Who's your favorite guy to draw?

10:25.311 --> 10:27.645
- Spider-Man is one of the greats.
- Superman, one of the greats,

10:27.647 --> 10:30.725
but drawing Daredevil is a pleasure,
so I would love to do those three.

10:30.725 --> 10:31.731
Man, absolutely.

10:33.233 --> 10:34.696
'Cause I mean, a lot of times, you know,

10:34.783 --> 10:36.869
your dad tries to get
you into what he likes,

10:37.001 --> 10:38.898
and it doesn't take, it
doesn't rub off on you.

10:39.068 --> 10:40.416
No, he didn't actually want me to be...

10:40.573 --> 10:42.272
He wanted me to be an
artist, but not a cartoonist,

10:42.272 --> 10:43.829
because this is a guy that
went up to his attic...

10:43.830 --> 10:45.444
You know, the attic door...
And he would disappear

10:45.511 --> 10:48.012
up there for days, come
back with a three-day growth,

10:48.014 --> 10:49.813
and he would be exhausted
from not sleeping,

10:49.815 --> 10:51.548
and he said the money was lousy.

10:51.550 --> 10:53.984
He says, "Be an artist. Do
anything else, advertising."

10:53.986 --> 10:56.086
Went into advertising,
illustration as a major,

10:56.088 --> 10:58.989
and I couldn't stop myself
from wanting to be a cartoonist.

10:58.991 --> 11:00.758
And I remembered Stan
Lee telling a story

11:00.760 --> 11:02.860
that when he was a young writer,
he'd go to cocktail parties.

11:02.862 --> 11:04.328
And they'd ask what he
did for... "I'm a writer."

11:04.330 --> 11:05.996
"What do you write?"
"I write comic books."

11:05.998 --> 11:07.731
And they would giggle, you know.

11:07.733 --> 11:09.566
And now Stan is who he is,

11:09.568 --> 11:11.402
but the conversation when I
was younger was the same thing:

11:11.404 --> 11:12.836
"You're an artist, what do you do?"

11:12.838 --> 11:14.672
"I'm a cartoonist." "Oh, really?"

11:14.674 --> 11:16.640
You know, giggle giggle.
And now, "I'm a cartoonist,

11:16.642 --> 11:18.943
"I work on graphic novels, Spider-Man,

11:18.945 --> 11:20.411
Batman, Superman."

11:20.413 --> 11:22.746
And suddenly: "Wow! You're an artist!"

11:22.748 --> 11:25.449
"Oh, first I was a
cartoonist, now I'm an artist."

11:25.451 --> 11:27.718
But you know, they changed
because of you, though.

11:27.720 --> 11:29.186
You played a big part in that.

11:29.188 --> 11:30.554
Well, I don't know
about me particularly,

11:30.556 --> 11:32.356
but Jack Kirby, John Buscema,

11:32.358 --> 11:35.092
John Romita, Stan Lee, that's
what changed everything.

11:46.790 --> 11:48.456
If you guys had to be
stranded on Gilligan's Island

11:48.458 --> 11:51.025
with only one of the castaways,
which one would it be?

11:51.027 --> 11:53.861
- Uh, I'd go with Mary Ann.
- Ooh!

11:53.863 --> 11:55.663
- This is young Mike? As in... Okay.
- Young Mike, yes.

11:55.665 --> 11:57.332
Young Mike goes out, gets stranded...

11:57.334 --> 11:59.200
- On a three-hour cruise.
- Three-hour cruise.

11:59.202 --> 12:02.570
- With just a movie starlet.
- No, no, that was Ginger.

12:02.572 --> 12:04.172
Mary Ann was the girl next door!

12:04.174 --> 12:05.373
- Oh, the country girl, okay.
- Yes.

12:05.375 --> 12:06.874
She's the wholesome girl.

12:06.876 --> 12:08.576
He knows he's got no
chance with a movie star.

12:08.578 --> 12:10.378
[all laugh]

12:10.380 --> 12:12.013
- What about you?
- Gosh, I mean, it's...

12:12.015 --> 12:13.681
I flip flop constantly,

12:13.683 --> 12:15.883
but I think right now
I'd go with the Professor.

12:15.885 --> 12:18.519
I think that every time
he had the right plan,

12:18.521 --> 12:21.356
it went awry, and I think
if it was just me and him,

12:21.358 --> 12:23.224
we wouldn't of even spend
a day on that island.

12:23.226 --> 12:26.060
- What about you?
- That is easy: Skipper.

12:26.062 --> 12:28.563
Really? Wasn't the
Skipper kind of a jerk?

12:28.565 --> 12:31.332
- Yeah. He reminds me of you.
- [all laugh]

12:31.334 --> 12:32.934
He's constantly frustrated

12:32.936 --> 12:35.403
with the foolishness
of those around him.

12:35.405 --> 12:37.438
That's right, I do work
with a couple of Gilligans.

12:37.440 --> 12:40.708
- Yeah.
- A couple? Hey, c'mon.

12:40.710 --> 12:43.878
A Gilligan, and a Gilligan
who thinks he's a professor.

12:43.880 --> 12:45.880
[all laugh]

12:45.882 --> 12:48.249
<i>[hard rock music]</i>

12:48.251 --> 12:49.350
<i>[laser fires]</i>

12:49.352 --> 12:50.585
<i>♪
♪</i>

12:50.587 --> 12:52.353
<i>[lasers fire]</i>

12:52.355 --> 12:55.390
- Okay, fellas, what do you suggest?
- We'd love a Spider-Man.

12:55.392 --> 12:56.791
- Dude, yeah.
- Okay.

12:56.793 --> 12:58.426
Not just one character... remember,

12:58.428 --> 12:59.894
we're dealing with Jim
Lee competition here.

12:59.896 --> 13:01.296
True, okay. You're
doing Superman now, so...

13:01.298 --> 13:02.730
- All right, that...
- Get a little D.C. love

13:02.732 --> 13:03.865
- in there.
- Yep, that would make sense.

13:03.867 --> 13:05.099
Maybe one more.

13:05.101 --> 13:07.535
- Who's your favorite guy to draw?
- Spider-Man's one of the greats.

13:07.537 --> 13:08.903
Superman, one of the greats,

13:08.905 --> 13:10.538
but drawing Daredevil is a pleasure,

13:10.540 --> 13:11.973
There's something about
the simple costume,

13:11.975 --> 13:14.609
and the two Ds, and the horns.

13:14.611 --> 13:17.145
I had my most fun doing
Daredevil, when I did Daredevil.

13:17.147 --> 13:18.946
So I would love to do those three.

13:18.948 --> 13:21.382
- Man, absolutely.
- So that's where we're going?

13:21.384 --> 13:23.418
All right, let's see what we can do.

13:23.420 --> 13:26.454
John Romita, Jr. is one
of the most dynamic artists

13:26.456 --> 13:28.256
of my favorite period of comics.

13:28.258 --> 13:30.525
I'll always think of
his work very fondly,

13:30.527 --> 13:32.860
because I remember buying
"Man Without Fear" every month.

13:32.862 --> 13:34.896
You bought "Spider-Man" every month.

13:34.898 --> 13:37.031
And so this was an artist
that you would talk about.

13:37.033 --> 13:38.966
Like, "I love this dude's
style, I love it a lot."

13:38.968 --> 13:41.069
How weird is it to be sitting there

13:41.071 --> 13:43.738
watching him draw years
later in the Secret Stash?

13:43.740 --> 13:45.707
It's truly unbelievable.

13:45.709 --> 13:48.776
For me to sit there and him
ask me, "Well, who do you want?"

13:48.778 --> 13:50.478
I mean, it's surreal,

13:50.480 --> 13:53.681
and it's one of those
moments I'll never forget.

13:53.683 --> 13:56.651
<i>[funky music]</i>

13:56.653 --> 13:58.619
My father once described drawing as

13:58.621 --> 14:00.621
"eliminating everything
that doesn't look like

14:00.623 --> 14:02.156
the figure on the paper."

14:02.158 --> 14:03.958
I wish it was as simple as that.

14:03.960 --> 14:08.329
<i>♪
♪</i>

14:08.331 --> 14:10.832
You grew up in an unbelievable period

14:10.834 --> 14:13.167
of comic book history, but yet you are

14:13.169 --> 14:15.403
making comic book history
yourself as an artist.

14:15.405 --> 14:18.840
You ever just sit... take a
step back and go like, "Wow"?

14:18.842 --> 14:20.641
Yeah, that is a pretty amazing thing.

14:20.643 --> 14:23.077
When Buscema was doing
Conan, I was on staff.

14:23.079 --> 14:25.980
I was like a kid, and
his pencils would come in,

14:25.982 --> 14:27.982
and on the backs of
each page was a warm up,

14:27.984 --> 14:30.551
and they were the most
beautiful illustrations.

14:30.553 --> 14:33.454
And he just didn't think of it
as anything other than doodles

14:33.456 --> 14:34.956
that he would warm up in the morning.

14:34.958 --> 14:36.791
He said he would get up
at 6:00, sit down by 7:00,

14:36.793 --> 14:39.160
then he would get on to
his eight pages a day,

14:39.162 --> 14:40.628
whatever he would lay out.

14:40.630 --> 14:43.164
And at the time I was
doing a page, maybe.

14:43.166 --> 14:44.866
And I would say, "How
am I supposed to do this

14:44.868 --> 14:46.534
and do better than that?"

14:46.536 --> 14:48.703
And then, Jack Kirby with
his gigantic cigar, saying,

14:48.705 --> 14:50.838
"You really want to do
this for a living, kid?"

14:50.840 --> 14:52.974
[all laugh]

14:52.976 --> 14:54.776
You inherit your father's name,

14:54.778 --> 14:57.812
and your father is a legend
who is exclent at his job,

14:57.814 --> 14:59.614
known the world over.

14:59.616 --> 15:02.417
What are the chances that
you can duplicate that career

15:02.419 --> 15:05.219
if not go beyond it, and
that's what his kid did, man.

15:05.221 --> 15:07.155
He had his own career,
where people weren't like,

15:07.157 --> 15:08.656
"Oh, you're John's kid."

15:08.658 --> 15:10.358
[all laugh]

15:10.360 --> 15:14.896
<i>[funky music]</i>

15:14.898 --> 15:17.698
My father always imbued
in me the opinion that

15:17.700 --> 15:20.168
there's always somebody bigger,
better, stronger, smarter,

15:20.170 --> 15:22.637
so get used to being with
your feet on the ground.

15:22.639 --> 15:25.440
It gives you incentive
every day to do better.

15:25.442 --> 15:27.875
And I look at Jim Lee's work.
I look at Frank Miller's work,

15:27.877 --> 15:30.745
and now there's Leinil Yus
and the whole generation,

15:30.747 --> 15:32.847
and you can sit back and be a fan,

15:32.849 --> 15:35.483
'cause there's one constant, and
that's the love of doing this.

15:35.485 --> 15:37.852
Nobody has ever said,
"I hate this business,

15:37.854 --> 15:39.320
I'm only doing this for a job."

15:39.322 --> 15:41.155
Nobody says that. They love it.

15:41.157 --> 15:44.692
And it makes a nice living,
but you can't make a nice living

15:44.694 --> 15:46.227
unless you really
enjoy what you're doing,

15:46.229 --> 15:48.396
'cause otherwise, it's just drudgery.

15:48.398 --> 15:51.399
<i>[exciting music]</i>

15:51.401 --> 15:55.570
<i>♪
♪</i>

15:55.572 --> 15:58.406
All right, guys, I think
I've come to an end.

15:58.408 --> 16:00.575
You ready for this?

16:00.577 --> 16:02.243
- [laughter]
- Awesome!

16:02.245 --> 16:03.978
If you couldn't afford
"Wonder Woman" number 1,

16:03.980 --> 16:05.546
this book would be
something you'd treasure.

16:14.008 --> 16:15.076
- Hey.
- Hey, guys.

16:15.076 --> 16:17.276
I called in about the
Treasury Edition Wonder Woman?

16:17.278 --> 16:19.078
Oh, that's right. I
put it aside for you.

16:19.080 --> 16:20.579
- Awesome.
- Here it is.

16:20.581 --> 16:21.880
- Aah.
- The Treasury Edition

16:21.882 --> 16:23.348
of "Wonder Woman" number 1.

16:23.350 --> 16:26.351
<i>[upbeat music]</i>

16:26.353 --> 16:29.755
<i>♪
♪</i>

16:29.757 --> 16:31.590
- This looks amazing!
- Huh?

16:31.592 --> 16:33.425
Wonder Woman kicking Nazi ass.

16:33.427 --> 16:34.793
[all laugh]

16:34.795 --> 16:36.128
- Right?
- Yeah.

16:36.130 --> 16:37.329
So, I have a question for you.

16:37.331 --> 16:38.831
This has always been on my mind.

16:38.833 --> 16:41.300
Why these "Treasury Edition" comics?

16:41.302 --> 16:43.702
Well, my first reasoning would be

16:43.704 --> 16:45.637
if you couldn't afford
"Wonder Woman" number 1,

16:45.639 --> 16:47.840
this book would be
something you'd treasure.

16:47.842 --> 16:49.708
- Nice.
- You know, back in 1975,

16:49.710 --> 16:51.910
D.C. was taking significant issues

16:51.912 --> 16:53.946
and doing facsimile editions

16:53.948 --> 16:56.281
of what the issue looked
like back in the '40s,

16:56.283 --> 16:57.649
giving a chance for readers, you know,

16:57.651 --> 17:00.686
to pick it up for the
small price of a buck.

17:00.688 --> 17:02.554
Remember the Treasury
Edition comic books?

17:02.556 --> 17:03.956
Of course. As a collector,

17:03.958 --> 17:05.691
it was always a pain in the neck.

17:05.693 --> 17:07.859
They don't make bags and
boards for books that big,

17:07.862 --> 17:10.028
but as a reader, I loved
the oversized treasury book.

17:10.030 --> 17:11.363
- Oh, yeah.
- They should do it

17:11.365 --> 17:13.132
for everything in life.

17:13.134 --> 17:15.000
They're like, "You like
this? it's bigger now!"

17:15.002 --> 17:17.069
[all laugh]

17:17.070 --> 17:18.403
So, you a big Wonder Woman fan?

17:18.405 --> 17:20.372
- Absolutely.
- What gave that away?

17:20.374 --> 17:22.473
Perhaps her Wonder
Woman fingernail polish?

17:22.476 --> 17:25.042
- Ooh!
- Or her Wonder Woman kicks.

17:25.045 --> 17:26.878
I mean, she's a legendary character.

17:26.881 --> 17:28.680
And she's one of those
people that... not...

17:28.682 --> 17:30.082
I want to be her, right?

17:30.084 --> 17:32.050
Are you excited to finally, finally

17:32.052 --> 17:33.418
see her represented in a movie?

17:33.420 --> 17:35.254
Oh, absolutely! Yeah.

17:35.256 --> 17:37.089
Go into any comic book
store in the world,

17:37.091 --> 17:39.091
Wonder Woman is represented somewhere,

17:39.093 --> 17:41.527
and now she's about to break mainstream,

17:41.529 --> 17:44.029
because of the Batman v Superman movie.

17:44.031 --> 17:45.697
That's the first cinematic treatment

17:45.699 --> 17:47.232
of the character, am I correct?

17:47.234 --> 17:48.667
They've never made a Wonder Woman movie.

17:48.669 --> 17:49.768
They've made a TV movie,

17:49.770 --> 17:51.370
and other than the cartoons,

17:51.372 --> 17:52.905
they haven't cracked the code

17:52.907 --> 17:54.506
with Wonder Woman since the '70s.

17:54.508 --> 17:56.241
Absolutely. Not since the days

17:56.243 --> 17:57.743
of Lynda Carter Wonder Woman

17:57.745 --> 17:59.611
has she been on the tips
of everybody's tongues

17:59.613 --> 18:01.180
as she is right now, right?

18:01.182 --> 18:03.448
Sounded filthier than
you meant it, but yes.

18:03.450 --> 18:05.284
[all laugh]

18:05.286 --> 18:09.087
So, um, what... what are we asking for?

18:09.089 --> 18:11.290
- $45.
- $45.

18:11.292 --> 18:13.759
If I had a lasso of truth
and I were to lasso you,

18:13.761 --> 18:16.728
what would you say to $25?

18:16.730 --> 18:18.931
I'd say... no.

18:18.933 --> 18:20.799
Lasso of truth says no.

18:20.801 --> 18:23.569
I'm not lying to you... I
would definitely say no to $25.

18:23.571 --> 18:25.971
Um... it's not in mint
condition, but if it was a mint,

18:25.973 --> 18:27.639
it'd go for a lot more than $45.

18:27.641 --> 18:29.274
- Mm-hmm.
- I mean, it's got a little...

18:29.276 --> 18:30.876
A little wear on the side there,

18:30.878 --> 18:33.312
but you know, overall,
it's a really nice copy.

18:33.314 --> 18:35.747
How about $35?

18:35.749 --> 18:38.217
How about I agree to $35,

18:38.219 --> 18:40.452
and I get hugs from each one of you?

18:40.454 --> 18:42.221
- I'll do it, yeah, you know.
- A hug.

18:42.223 --> 18:43.755
Awesome! Then you've
got a deal, my friend.

18:43.757 --> 18:45.457
All right. All right.

18:45.459 --> 18:47.559
- Thanks.
- Thank you so much.

18:47.561 --> 18:48.727
- Not at all.
- Thank you for this.

18:48.729 --> 18:50.329
[laughs] Thank you so much.

18:50.331 --> 18:52.030
- Appreciate it. Bye.
- Bye.

18:53.466 --> 18:56.468
<i>[funky music]</i>

18:56.470 --> 18:59.404
<i>♪
♪</i>

18:59.406 --> 19:02.641
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

19:02.643 --> 19:05.310
All right, guys, I think
I've come to an end.

19:05.312 --> 19:06.945
I could probably work
on it another half hour,

19:06.947 --> 19:08.513
but I'm gonna get too anal, so...

19:08.515 --> 19:10.282
- You guys ready for this?
- Oh, my God, yes.

19:10.284 --> 19:11.984
All right.

19:11.986 --> 19:15.520
Let the pigeons loose. [laughter]

19:15.522 --> 19:16.989
- Oh, wow!
- That's... that's insane.

19:16.991 --> 19:20.158
Spider-Man, wearing your logo? Awesome.

19:20.160 --> 19:22.761
- It will forever hang...
- Oh, I appreciate it.

19:22.763 --> 19:23.996
Here at the Stash.

19:23.998 --> 19:25.430
Wow, man.

19:25.432 --> 19:27.432
You know that made my
web shooters go off.

19:27.434 --> 19:28.767
[all laugh]

19:28.769 --> 19:30.636
Come on, that's fantastic.

19:30.638 --> 19:33.605
All right, guys. Do
with it as you see fit.

19:33.607 --> 19:34.973
Oh, my God.

19:34.975 --> 19:36.341
- Good to see you.
- Thank you so much.

19:36.343 --> 19:37.709
- My pleasure, guys.
- Thank you so much

19:37.711 --> 19:38.844
- for coming here.
- Great seeing you again.

19:38.846 --> 19:40.379
You guys take care. Be good.

19:40.381 --> 19:42.114
- You too, thanks.
- Oh, my God, look at that!

19:42.116 --> 19:44.149
Can you imagine if this was a real team?

19:44.151 --> 19:46.184
Superman, Spider-Man, and Daredevil?

19:46.186 --> 19:47.552
- Yeah.
- I know you don't know

19:47.554 --> 19:50.289
what you're looking at, here,
but this is a one of a kind.

19:50.291 --> 19:53.659
You're just never going to
walk into any store in the world

19:53.661 --> 19:57.129
and see a John Romita,
Jr. original pencil piece

19:57.131 --> 20:01.066
with these characters,
wearing the logo of logos.

20:01.068 --> 20:03.302
Spider-Man, wearing our colors?

20:03.304 --> 20:04.836
One of us now.

20:04.838 --> 20:06.738
Wow, that poor bastard's
fallen on hard times.

20:06.740 --> 20:09.975
[all laugh]

20:09.977 --> 20:11.243
You want me to fix this one for you?

20:11.245 --> 20:12.744
- [all laugh]
- No!

20:12.746 --> 20:13.912
Jackass.

20:13.914 --> 20:15.380
Gotta feel lucky as hell

20:15.382 --> 20:17.683
to live in a world where, like,

20:17.685 --> 20:21.620
not only can you appreciate
someone's artwork from afar,

20:21.622 --> 20:23.889
but now they'll come down
to the comic book store

20:23.891 --> 20:25.857
and draw for you, or with you,

20:25.859 --> 20:27.693
and show you how it's done, and stuff.

20:27.695 --> 20:30.529
Then to learn that they're
actually a human being,

20:30.531 --> 20:32.297
interesting, funny, a good guy.

20:32.299 --> 20:34.900
Just because somebody's
exceptional at their job

20:34.902 --> 20:36.835
beyond comprehension,

20:36.837 --> 20:39.104
doesn't mean they can't
just be a normal person, man.

20:39.106 --> 20:40.405
He's definitely one of those.

20:40.407 --> 20:42.040
I thought I proved that.

20:42.042 --> 20:44.509
[all laugh]

20:44.511 --> 20:46.378
Great Caesar's ghost!
We're out of time, man.

20:46.380 --> 20:48.046
For "Comic Book Men," I'm Kevin Smith.

20:48.048 --> 20:49.715
- Bryan Johnson.
- Walt Flanagan.

20:49.717 --> 20:51.416
- Mike Zapcic.
- Ming Chen.

20:51.418 --> 20:53.285
Remember, kids, you
don't need magical powers

20:53.287 --> 20:55.420
to be a wonder woman or a super man.

20:55.422 --> 20:57.055
Just don't be a dick. Good night.
